{
  "info": {
    "_postman_id": "f0r6e-m1c0-11ec-t10n-000000000001",
    "name": "ForgeML Control Plane (v1)",
    "description": "The ForgeML V1 control-plane API.\n\n**Before you start**\n\n1. PostgreSQL 16 must be running and migrated (`alembic upgrade head`).\n2. The backend must be running (`python -m forgeml`), by default on http://127.0.0.1:8000.\n3. You need a `.forge` file. Build one with:\n   `python3 scripts/forge_pack.py examples/hello-model`\n\n**Key concepts**\n\n- A package is identified by the SHA-256 of its bytes. Uploading identical bytes twice yields **one** package (ADR-003).\n- `POST /v1/packages` returns **202 and an operation**, not a package (ADR-006). Poll the operation, then read the package.\n- A **rejected** package still produces a **succeeded** operation: the validation ran, and the verdict lives on the package. An operation only *fails* when the platform could not do the work.\n- Every mutation requires an `Idempotency-Key`. Replaying a request returns the original operation and does no work twice.\n- Every response carries `X-Request-ID`, which is also the operation's `correlation_id`. The server generates it and ignores any you send (ADR-015).\n\n**There is no authentication.** Keep this on a trusted network.",
    "schema": "https://schema.getpostman.com/json/collection/v2.1.0/collection.json"
  },
  "variable": [],
  "event": [
    {
      "listen": "test",
      "script": {
        "type": "text/javascript",
        "exec": [
          "// Applies to every request in the collection.",
          "pm.test('Server issued a correlation id (ADR-015)', function () {",
          "    pm.response.to.have.header('X-Request-ID');",
          "    const id = pm.response.headers.get('X-Request-ID');",
          "    pm.expect(id).to.match(/^[0-9a-f]{8}-[0-9a-f]{4}-4[0-9a-f]{3}-[89ab][0-9a-f]{3}-[0-9a-f]{12}$/i);",
          "    pm.collectionVariables.set('correlationId', id);",
          "});",
          "",
          "pm.test('Response is JSON', function () {",
          "    pm.expect(pm.response.headers.get('Content-Type')).to.include('application/json');",
          "});",
          "",
          "// Any error must use the frozen ForgeML envelope (docs 12).",
          "if (pm.response.code >= 400) {",
          "    pm.test('Error uses the frozen envelope', function () {",
          "        const body = pm.response.json();",
          "        pm.expect(body).to.have.property('code');",
          "        pm.expect(body).to.have.property('message');",
          "        pm.expect(body).to.have.property('request_id');",
          "        pm.expect(body).to.not.have.property('detail');",
          "    });",
          "}"
        ]
      }
    }
  ],
  "item": [
    {
      "name": "Health",
      "description": "Operational probes. Liveness answers \"is the process up\"; readiness answers \"can it actually serve\", which since Module 2 means PostgreSQL must answer.",
      "item": [
        {
          "name": "Liveness — GET /healthz",
          "request": {
            "method": "GET",
            "header": [],
            "url": { "raw": "{{baseUrl}}/healthz", "host": ["{{baseUrl}}"], "path": ["healthz"] },
            "description": "**Is the process alive?**\n\nAnswers 200 as soon as the process is up. It does **not** check the database — that is what `/readyz` is for. An orchestrator should use this as its liveness probe, or it will kill a healthy process during a database blip.\n\n**200** — `{status: \"ok\", service, version}`"
          },
          "response": [
            {
              "name": "200 OK",
              "originalRequest": { "method": "GET", "header": [], "url": { "raw": "{{baseUrl}}/healthz" } },
              "status": "OK",
              "code": 200,
              "header": [{ "key": "Content-Type", "value": "application/json" }],
              "body": "{\n  \"status\": \"ok\",\n  \"service\": \"forgeml-control-plane\",\n  \"version\": \"0.1.0\"\n}"
            }
          ],
          "event": [
            {
              "listen": "test",
              "script": {
                "type": "text/javascript",
                "exec": [
                  "pm.test('200 OK', () => pm.response.to.have.status(200));",
                  "const body = pm.response.json();",
                  "pm.test('Reports ok', () => pm.expect(body.status).to.eql('ok'));",
                  "pm.test('Identifies the service', () => pm.expect(body.service).to.eql('forgeml-control-plane'));",
                  "pm.test('Exposes no extra fields', () => pm.expect(Object.keys(body).sort()).to.eql(['service','status','version']));"
                ]
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "name": "Readiness — GET /readyz",
          "request": {
            "method": "GET",
            "header": [],
            "url": { "raw": "{{baseUrl}}/readyz", "host": ["{{baseUrl}}"], "path": ["readyz"] },
            "description": "**Can this process actually serve?**\n\nExecutes `SELECT 1` against the metadata database.\n\n**200** — ready.\n\n**503 `dependency_unavailable`** — PostgreSQL is not reachable, or `FORGEML_DATABASE_URL` is not set. The control plane cannot serve a single package request in this state. Fix the database before going further; every other request in this collection will fail."
          },
          "response": [
            {
              "name": "200 Ready",
              "originalRequest": { "method": "GET", "header": [], "url": { "raw": "{{baseUrl}}/readyz" } },
              "status": "OK",
              "code": 200,
              "header": [{ "key": "Content-Type", "value": "application/json" }],
              "body": "{\n  \"status\": \"ready\",\n  \"service\": \"forgeml-control-plane\",\n  \"version\": \"0.1.0\"\n}"
            },
            {
              "name": "503 Database unavailable",
              "originalRequest": { "method": "GET", "header": [], "url": { "raw": "{{baseUrl}}/readyz" } },
              "status": "Service Unavailable",
              "code": 503,
              "header": [{ "key": "Content-Type", "value": "application/json" }],
              "body": "{\n  \"code\": \"dependency_unavailable\",\n  \"message\": \"The metadata database is unavailable.\",\n  \"request_id\": \"1bc48560-aae5-4dbb-94ec-56f85b2ac581\"\n}"
            }
          ],
          "event": [
            {
              "listen": "test",
              "script": {
                "type": "text/javascript",
                "exec": [
                  "pm.test('Ready (200). A 503 means PostgreSQL is unreachable — fix that first.', function () {",
                  "    pm.response.to.have.status(200);",
                  "});",
                  "pm.test('Reports ready', () => pm.expect(pm.response.json().status).to.eql('ready'));"
                ]
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "name": "OpenAPI schema — GET /v1/openapi.json",
          "request": {
            "method": "GET",
            "header": [],
            "url": { "raw": "{{baseUrl}}/v1/openapi.json", "host": ["{{baseUrl}}"], "path": ["v1", "openapi.json"] },
            "description": "The published schema — the API's source of truth.\n\n**Swagger UI and ReDoc are deliberately disabled.** Docs 11 keeps the control plane on an administrative network until an authorization ADR exists, and a browsable console on an unauthenticated, code-executing control plane invites exactly the exposure that decision has not been made yet. The schema itself is published so you can generate a client."
          },
          "response": [],
